Goodness the 3 experiences I had at Anita's set the base line and the high bar for my trip to New Orleans.  This place felt the most authentic of every spot I visited.  First trip was just a quick stop by for some black coffee and it was honestly the best drip coffee I've ever had.  Second time I was hung over from a fun night on Bourbon Street and nursed myself back to life with an Iced Tea.  When I told the matriarch (best way to describe the one person I haven't asked for their name to review) of the establishment enjoyed jesting with me and then offered a bartenders gingerale to settle my stomach...floored by her kindness.  I knew I had to come back to try the Liver as it would be my first time ever and it's so world famous they have masks promoting it.  So very delicious and the serving size was so generous I had leftovers twice.  The Western omelet was also so very delicious.  When I asked for hash browns she asked if we wanted to add peppers and a few other delicious add on to make the best loaded potatoes ever!  Thank you so much for such a phenomenal experience and for sharing the history of Anita's from pre-Katrina days.  I'll be back as soon as I am able  ❤💜💚

Anita's advertises itself as "world famous." After a much anticipated visit, I don't understand at all what could make this place world famous.  Mediocrity, perhaps? At about noon on a weekday, I ordered the liver and onions with eggs. My food arrived in about the time I expected, so nothing spectacular there, but I'll give them a positive stroke for getting hot food to the table. The eggs were cooked to order, almost exactly to the "over medium" that I asked for. The liver--one slice of usual thickness--was cooked properly, but a little sinewy. It was covered with a large portion of average brown gravy and smothered fine-cut onion strings. If there was a standout item, it was the hash browns. These were 3/4-inch cubes of perfectly tender potatoes, seasoned well. They weren't spicy or salty. Let's say they were perfectly prepared for the addition of salt and pepper at the table. The service was friendly and reasonably prompt, but the restaurant was far below its modest seating capacity, too. I might return, but Anita's Restaurant is not a place I'll make a special trip to visit.
